\section{Background of the Study}

Games have been a significant part of most people's lives, be it to play competitively,
as an E-Sport, or as a short escape from reality. Games have been everywhere. Almost
everyone has seen or even played such entertainment. The diversity of the games offers
various experiences, whether a person wants to competitively shoot someone in-game or
just wants to live on farmland. In particular, indie games contribute greatly to the
diverse line of games that an individual can play.

A game is an art form, a combination of various media like music, art, storytelling,
and more to create an ``experience,'' be it real or surreal. Some games want to tell a
story, while others want to make you feel something like competitiveness, sports, or
something ridiculous like playing as a squirrel with a gun. Nowadays, popular indie
games often have that simple yet addicting and entertaining concept; examples are
Minecraft which was once an indie game developed by Markus Alexej Persson; Stardew
Valley, which is a very popular game; and Terraria, which is very similar to Minecraft
but focuses more on the story and combat aspects. These games all have something in
common, and that is making use of nature in an entertaining way.

Game development, especially in the Philippines, is rather less heard of, specifically
in any other province, as most indulge in the mainstream or mostly foreign-made.
However, we would like to bring a different perspective. A project, not typically about
what people would think of, but rather, a different one. The game that would bring an
experience of simplicity and the life most people have or have never experienced before:
exploring the unique view and experiencing the simple life of a province.

Supporting and promoting local tourism through gamification provides an angle that
can be a bridge between innovation and preservation of culture and natural beauty of
communities. In particular, the Bicol Province offers a lot when it comes to inspirations
that can be used for game development, whether it be the mythical stories, the beautiful
landmarks scattered around the whole province, or the culture when it comes to devotion.
There are many parts in the Bicol province that have inherent characteristics, and one
such place is the municipality of Tinambac, from its largest region, Camarines Sur.

Salubako is a gamified application designed to guide and show a glimpse of the culture,
natural beauty, and unique attractions of Tinambac. Whether you are an interested
player, a local explorer, or a curious traveler, Salubako transforms the player's
journey into a thrilling quest filled with challenges and discoveries. Salubako offers
collective memories and experiences by exploring Tinambac's scenic views, vibrant
communities, and cultural landmarks. Through interactive games and location-based
mini-games, you will earn rewards and, at the same time, interesting information about
Tinambac. This project is also in alignment with the United Nation's Sustainable
Development Goals (SDGs), SDG 8 (Decent Work and Economic Growth) as well as SDG 11
(Sustainable Cities and Communities), to be more specific.

\section{Review of Related Literature}
\addtocontents{toc}{\protect\setcounter{tocdepth}{1}}

\subsection*{Cultural Heritage and Education in Games}

Serious games and gamified applications have demonstrated significant capacity to
enhance user participation in cultural heritage by producing emotional immersion and
behavioral change toward preservation, as evidenced by frameworks such as the Experience
Economy and the Stimulus-Organism-Response theory applied in game design contexts
\citep{zhang2024} \citep{dankov2023} \citep{wu2023} \citep{cassone2021}.

Alternative reality games, mixed reality systems, and wearable mobile learning tools
have been shown to significantly outperform conventional instruction in promoting student
engagement, emotional involvement, and awareness of cultural preservation and sustainable
development \citep{lin2024} \citep{huang2023} \citep{stylianidis2025} \citep{tian2025}.

Digital transformation of cultural heritage education through platforms, virtual reality
content creation, and bichronous learning modes combining asynchronous digital games
with synchronous online courses produces superior learning outcomes, knowledge
acquisition, and student satisfaction compared to either approach alone
\citep{lai2025} \citep{li2025} \citep{guo2025} \citep{diblas2010}.

Heritage education in higher institutions increasingly integrates intangible cultural
heritage through quantitative and qualitative methods, revealing that such education
significantly enhances students' cultural identity, respect for traditional practices,
and covariant relationships between cultural tourism integration and heritage education
\citep{xu2023} \citep{yan2023} \citep{brumana2022} \citep{santos2024}.

Digital and cultural heritage competencies among young learners promote resilience and
readiness for digital transformation, though low digital literacy and high dropout rates
in certain contexts continue to challenge effective integration across European
educational systems \citep{orphanidou2024} \citep{jangra2025} \citep{lofstrom2024}.

Pre-service and in-service teachers predominantly hold surface-level, material
conceptions of cultural heritage with limited methodological expertise, pointing to
persistent gaps in teacher education programs across national curricula in preparing
educators for culturally responsive heritage instruction
\citep{cuenca2021} \citep{miguelrevilla2024} \citep{gulya2024} \citep{pitri2025}.

Experiential and interdisciplinary heritage education programs, including
learning-through-the-arts and archaeological heritage education approaches, demonstrate
significant development of cognitive and socio-affective competencies among learners in
multicultural and diverse educational settings
\citep{gomezhurtado2021} \citep{gonzalezsanz2022} \citep{greaves2023} \citep{castrocalvino2020}.

Community-centered heritage education initiatives that actively involve local
stakeholders, families, and local authorities achieve high methodological appreciation
and meaningful learning outcomes, reinforcing that sustainable heritage preservation
requires multi-stakeholder participation rather than purely institutional management
\citep{castrocalvino2020} \citep{greaves2023} \citep{santos2024} \citep{abdallah2023}.

Constructivist game design frameworks embedded in museum learning and heritage
curricula, along with anti-essentialist approaches that explore fluid and hybrid cultural
identities, support deeper cultural understanding and position heritage education as a
transformative space rather than a vehicle for fixed cultural narratives
\citep{wang2025} \citep{park2023} \citep{lopezfernandez2021} \citep{perezguilarte2023}.

\subsection*{Tourist Behavior and Experience Design}

Participatory learning plays a central role in people-centered heritage conservation
by engaging communities and diverse audiences in knowledge co-creation and transmission,
with digital tools examined across four dimensions---cultural heritage, education,
participation, and digital tool effectiveness---demonstrating varied strengths and
limitations in supporting these goals \citep{jangra2025} \citep{santos2024} \citep{greaves2023}.

Local cultural elements embedded in game design, such as Filipino traditional games
(Laro ng Lahi), Japanese region-specific smartphone applications, and Tanka
ballad-inspired games, demonstrate that localized game development fosters community
identity, promotes cultural appreciation, and serves as a catalyst for sustainable local
tourism and development \citep{roel2021} \citep{yasumasa2024} \citep{wu2022}.

Italian and Indian mobile game projects that integrate regional cultural heritage into
their design function as strategic marketing tools for cultural institutions and local
administrations, serving dual purposes of boosting tourism and promoting cultural
activities while reflecting locally relevant narratives and practices
\citep{samanta2022} \citep{zeiler2021} \citep{yasumasa2024}.

Authentic Indigenous sound, music, and cultural expression within game design resist
stereotyping, promote identity preservation, and contribute to meaningful representation,
as demonstrated by analyses of Indigenous-designed game music and sound studies that
challenge oversimplified portrayals of cultural communities
\citep{galloway2024} \citep{xu2023} \citep{wu2023}.

Role-playing games and interactive text-based narratives serve as effective
historiographic instruments by enabling players to engage with alternative historical
scenarios, emotional memory, and cultural narratives, demonstrating the potential of
game-based storytelling in transmitting cultural legacy across generations
\citep{santos2015} \citep{belov2022} \citep{cassone2021}.

Virtual reality and augmented reality applications for cultural heritage transmission,
particularly for recording and reconstructing intangible heritage such as traditional
crafts and performing arts, significantly promote both extrinsic and intrinsic motivation
through immersion, interactivity, and enhanced educational experiences
\citep{tian2025} \citep{stylianidis2025} \citep{lai2025}.

Experiential heritage learning approaches in formal education sites, such as the
Imperial Citadel of Thang Long-Hanoi, yield strong skill formation outcomes, with
approximately 94\% of students demonstrating effective cultural competency development
through hands-on, observation-based heritage activities
\citep{tran2024} \citep{gonzalezsanz2022} \citep{gomezhurtado2021}.

The integration of digital cultural heritage into compulsory curricula varies
significantly across national contexts, with policy analyses revealing that divergent
conceptualizations of heritage education in Estonia, Finland, and Sweden produce
differing impacts on students' sense of national identity and civic participation
\citep{lofstrom2024} \citep{jagielska2021} \citep{santos2024}.

Game mechanics that incorporate player preferences, motivations, character design
quality, and immersive in-game environments significantly enhance player engagement,
emotional investment, and overall gameplay experience, with strong artistic alignment
and culturally resonant character design emerging as critical determinants of game
attractiveness \citep{li2023} \citep{dzjanakhmetov2024} \citep{kou2023} \citep{vries2023}.

\subsection*{Gamification in Tourism and Travel}

Systematic literature reviews on gamification in tourism and hospitality consistently
identify loyalty, engagement, and behavioral intention as central outcomes of gamified
interventions, with scholars calling for more integrated theoretical models to address
the fragmented nature of existing literature across the sector
\citep{pasca2021} \citep{pradhan2023} \citep{malik2024}.

Tourists' engagement with gamified systems is primarily driven by intrinsic motivations
such as curiosity, exploration, and achievement, with distinct player typologies
identified through Q methodology, suggesting that effective gamification must be tailored
to diverse tourist profiles and psychological needs \citep{aebli2019} \citep{shen2020} \citep{chan2024}.

Mobile gamification and augmented reality game elements embedded in digital platforms
significantly enhance tourists' visit intention and can revitalize declining destinations
by renewing tourist interest through immersive, game-based experiences
\citep{ting2025} \citep{jo2025} \citep{fan2022}.

Gamification adoption meaningfully strengthens destination branding, tourist loyalty,
and digital destination image, with customer engagement mediating the relationship
between gamification adoption and brand outcomes, and gamified content improving
tourists' emotional connection to heritage destinations
\citep{aboushouk2021} \citep{zhang2025} \citep{chan2024}.

The combination of gamification and goal priming in virtual reality tourism experiences
produces stronger hedonic and utilitarian outcomes than either strategy alone, while
meta-analyses confirm that immersive technologies such as AR and VR significantly
elevate experiential quality, satisfaction, and behavioral intentions
\citep{liu2025} \citep{fan2022} \citep{jo2025}.

Interactive text-based narratives and serious games that connect players to emotional
memories and nostalgia have demonstrated capacity for evoking personal reflection and
deeper narrative engagement, reinforcing gamification's role as a mechanism for
affective rather than purely cognitive tourism experiences
\citep{cassone2021} \citep{pasca2021} \citep{aebli2019}.

Location-based and mixed-reality games encourage players to engage more deeply with
physical environments, bridging the gap between digital gameplay and real-world place
attachment, contributing to more meaningful tourism encounters and local cultural
appreciation \citep{huck2015} \citep{jo2025} \citep{fan2022}.

Gamification in the metaverse and virtual event tourism functions as a double-edged
mechanism, capable of either enriching or diminishing perceived authenticity depending
on design execution, underscoring the critical importance of thoughtful and culturally
sensitive gamified design in digital tourism contexts
\citep{flavian2024} \citep{zhang2025} \citep{malik2024}.

Gamified cultural heritage applications deployed as strategic marketing tools in local
government and tourism administration contexts effectively boost cultural engagement,
audience development, and civic involvement, extending the reach of heritage
preservation efforts beyond institutional walls into community and tourism ecosystems
\citep{cassone2021} \citep{samanta2022} \citep{aboushouk2021} \citep{zhang2025}.

