\section{Synthesis of the State-of-the-Art}

The body of literature reviewed reflects a rapidly expanding scholarly interest in the
intersection of cultural heritage, education, digital technology, and gamification.
Across these thematic domains, several converging patterns emerge.

First, the literature consistently establishes that traditional approaches to cultural
heritage education---face-to-face instruction, printed materials, and on-site
visits---are insufficient for contemporary learners, particularly digital natives of
Generation Z. Scholars such as Di Blas and Poggi (2010), Brumana et al.\ (2022), and
Orphanidou et al.\ (2024) document this pedagogical gap and call for innovative,
technology-enhanced alternatives. In response, digital tools including augmented reality
(AR), virtual reality (VR), mixed reality (MR), alternative reality games (ARGs), and
serious games have been studied as immersive substitutes that deepen learner engagement,
emotional connection, and knowledge retention
\citep{stylianidis2025} \citep{tian2025} \citep{huang2023} \citep{lin2024}.

Second, gamification emerges as a particularly potent mechanism for driving both
cultural engagement and behavioral change toward heritage preservation. Zhang et al.\
(2024) and Wu et al.\ (2023) theorize this through frameworks like the Experience
Economy and SOR theory, demonstrating that games capable of producing emotional
immersion lead to stronger identification with and commitment to cultural heritage.
Dankov and Dankova (2023) and Cassone and Viola (2021) extend this by showing that
gamified experiences move beyond cognitive learning into affective and civic
engagement---players do not merely learn about heritage, they are moved to protect it.
This is reinforced in tourism literature, where gamification has been shown to improve
destination branding, tourist loyalty, and digital destination image
\citep{aboushouk2021} \citep{zhang2025}.

Third, the role of local and intangible cultural heritage receives growing attention.
Studies on Filipino traditional games \citep{roel2021}, Chinese intangible cultural
heritage in MMORPGs and LARPs \citep{xu2023}, Japanese localized game development
\citep{yasumasa2024}, and Indian regional game narratives \citep{zeiler2021} all
underscore the value of embedding culturally specific elements into game design.
Galloway's work on Indigenous sound and music in games further highlights how authentic
cultural expression within digital media resists stereotyping and promotes identity
preservation. These studies collectively argue that games localized around
community-specific cultural markers produce deeper resonance and more meaningful
engagement than generalized cultural content.

Fourth, teacher education and curriculum integration surface as persistent structural
challenges. Cuenca-L\'{o}pez et al.\ (2021), Miguel-Revilla et al.\ (2024), and
L\"{o}fstr\"{o}m and Virta (2024) reveal that pre-service and in-service teachers hold
largely material, surface-level conceptions of heritage, lack methodological expertise
for heritage instruction, and operate within national curricula that inconsistently
prioritize heritage education. Without strong teacher preparation, even well-designed
heritage education programs lose their transformative potential in the classroom.

Fifth, participatory and community-centered approaches are recognized as essential for
sustainable cultural preservation. Santos et al.\ (2024), Greaves et al.\ (2023), and
Jangra and Wang (2025) all emphasize that heritage conservation is not merely a matter
of institutional management but requires the active participation of local communities,
diverse audiences, and multiple stakeholders in co-creating heritage knowledge and
meaning.

\section{Gap Bridge of the Study}

Despite the richness of existing scholarship, several significant gaps remain that point toward the need for the present study. While the literature broadly affirms that gamification and serious games effectively promote cultural heritage engagement, most studies are situated in European, East Asian, or Western institutional contexts. Research grounded in the specific cultural, educational, and community realities of the Philippines, particularly those that draw from Filipino indigenous games such as Laro ng Lahi as design scaffolding, remains notably underrepresented. Roel et al.\ (2021) provide a preliminary foundation, but the potential of Filipino traditional games as a structured basis for digital heritage game design remains largely unexplored. Furthermore, while emotional engagement and cultural identity have been separately studied, there is limited empirical work examining how locally embedded game narratives simultaneously strengthen cultural identity, foster intergenerational knowledge transmission, and promote sustainable heritage preservation behaviors among Filipino learners. The distinction matters: many studies measure short-term engagement or knowledge gain, but fewer trace the longer-term attitudinal and behavioral shifts, particularly cultural attachment and preservation intention, that heritage education ultimately aims to produce. Additionally, the bichronous learning model proposed by Li et al.\ (2025) and the constructivist game design framework of Wang et al.\ (2025) are promising but have not been applied or tested in informal community heritage settings or within indigenous cultural frameworks common in the Philippine archipelago. Bridging formal game-based learning theory with community-centered participatory design remains an open methodological frontier. Finally, while teacher preparation and curriculum integration are identified as structural weaknesses in heritage education broadly \citep{gulya2024} \citep{pitri2025}, there is a scarcity of studies examining how game-based pedagogical tools designed around local Filipino culture can be embedded into teacher education programs to build culturally responsive competencies among pre-service educators. The present study addresses these gaps by developing a culturally grounded, game-based heritage education framework anchored in Filipino cultural identity, drawing on indigenous game traditions, and examining its impact on learner engagement, cultural attachment, and preservation intention within a Philippine educational context.

\section{Theoretical Framework}

This study wishes to look into how a gamified approach to a tour around landmarks in
the municipality of Tinambac, with the aim of promoting local tourism through the
beauty of rural areas, the culture, and the relevant information that will be presented
to the target players. Therefore, Heritage Values Theory (1903), which serves as the
foundational theory of this study, was a concept proposed by the Austrian art historian
Alois Riegl, who identified key values---specifically age value, historical value, and
intentional commemorative value---that form the basis of, or stand in opposition to,
modern heritage management.

On top of that, the Gamification Theory (2002), coined by Nick Pelling back in 2002
while developing a business aimed at creating game-like interfaces for electronic
devices, will be added as the pivotal theory for this study. The concept of gamification
is now often used in many sectors, as it conforms to the human nature of finding things
that are entertaining to do as something worth putting more attention into. Lastly, the
Technology Acceptance Model (1986), proposed by Fred Davis for his dissertation, argued
that a person's intent to use a system is driven by their perceptions, not necessarily
the actual reality of the tech. These theories enable the study to dive deeper into the
intricacies of identifying the factors that might and might not complement applications
that are fundamentally gamified. Figure 1 on the next page
visually represents the theoretical framework of this study.

