\chapter{Methodology}

This section discussed the research methodology employed by the study.

\section{Research Design}

The research employs a quantitative design to systematically gather and analyze data
relevant to the development of a gamified experience reflecting a tour around a
provincial setting, specifically in the municipality of Tinambac from the province of
Camarines Sur in the Bicol region. This approach involves collecting structured
responses through digital surveys, which will enable the researchers to evaluate and
interpret statistical trends. Demographic details, as well as participants' knowledge
and perceptions of Bicol's cultural elements, will form the core of the data. The study
prioritizes a broad age range, particularly targeting individuals aged 13 and above,
with a focus on students and youth. Data analysis will rely on descriptive statistics,
employing tools such as automated reports and visualizations generated through Google
Forms. To ensure reliability and validity, only respondents fitting the specified
criteria will be included, while ethical considerations like confidentiality and
informed consent will be strictly observed. This design aims to generate meaningful
insights into how real-life landmarks can be effectively integrated into game design,
thereby achieving the study's objectives of gamifying the touring experience around
landmarks in Tinambac.

\section{Population and Sampling}

The study's target participants are 13 years old and above, and narrowing the
demographics between being a student or not helped in getting a better understanding
of a participant's awareness of this study's locale. The area where participants were
taken from was mostly from within and the peripheries of Naga City. With the goal of
gaining a better understanding of the target population's perception regarding their
knowledge of the research locale in terms of awareness and interest in traveling to it,
the target population was estimated to be beyond 15; this is considering the need for
the participants' time and effort in testing the gamified app and consequently answering
the survey form.

\section{Research Locale}

This study was conducted in the municipality of Tinambac, located in the province of Camarines Sur, Region V (Bicol Region), Philippines. Tinambac is a coastal municipality composed of 44 barangays, known for its scenic beaches, historical landmarks, and rich cultural heritage rooted in Bicolano tradition. Among its notable sites are the Municipal Hall of Tinambac in Barangay Binalay, the St. Paschal Baylon Parish Church in Barangay San Pascual, Caloco Beach in Barangay Caloco, and Cagliliog Beach Resort in Barangay Cagliliog, all of which were selected as the primary landmark subjects for this study. Despite its cultural and natural wealth, Tinambac remains a relatively lesser-known destination, with limited digital presence and few modern platforms dedicated to promoting its local tourism. The user testing and survey administration, however, were carried out within and around Naga City, given its proximity to the study locale and the concentration of the target respondent population in the area. Naga City served as the practical base for choosing the study's participants, while Tinambac itself provided the cultural and geographical context that grounded the entirety of the gamified application's content and design.

\section{Research Instrument}

The data collection method used for this research is by means of digital survey forms
to gather information about the necessary details that can be incorporated into the
project. The data collected will contain basic demographic details (optional name) and
questions about the player's experience playing the game. This study ensures that
respondents will have prior knowledge as to the study's intents and objectives, and
that all questions will be relevant to the study's purpose and objectives.

\section{Ethical Considerations}

In order to observe the confidentiality of the survey respondents' responses, the
researchers ensured that they would be aware of the type of data that will be collected
on the survey sessions. The researchers did this by handing out a copy of the letter of
consent to them. Personal data from the responses, such as names, would remain optional
to ensure the confidentiality of the respondents' inputs. However, not-so-sensitive
data, like gaming preferences, was collected for categorizing responses from the diverse
crowd. The study did not ask very sensitive personal questions but rather gather some
data relevant to the gaming experience of the game and its effect on the players.

Names to be featured in the game: names of places, considering the fact that this
research presented an alternative way of promoting local tourism for the municipality of
Tinambac, and names of people, which were purely fictitious names to avoid copyright
and affiliation, and so will the story and the timeline. The theme of the planned game
will not contain any sensitive and disturbing themes. Minor graphics, design, and
storytelling content shall be fit to a certain player age bracket target. Player
discretion is advised.

\section{Statistical Treatment of Data}

In retrospect to the utilized data-gathering tool in this study, the researchers opted
to use descriptive statistics to analyze and interpret the collected data gathered from
the respondents. This analysis was done using the process of calculating the weighted
mean. Interpretation of the resulting data, on the other hand, was done using the
Likert Scale.

\textbf{Weighted Mean.} The weighted mean is calculated by multiplying each value by
its weight, summing these products, and then dividing the total by the sum of all the
weights.

\[
\text{Weighted Average} = \frac{\sum wx}{\sum w}
\]

Where: $\Sigma =$ ``sum up''; $w =$ the weight for each data point;
$x =$ the value of each data point.

\textbf{Frequency Mean.} The frequency distribution displays the number of occurrences
(frequency or $f$) of each distinct value or category within a dataset. It provides a
summary of the distribution of values or categories for interpretation and analysis of
the data.

\textbf{Percentage Distribution.} Percentage distribution is a statistical tool used
to show how a whole is divided among different categories.

\[
\text{Percentage} = \left(\frac{f}{n}\right) \times 100\%
\]

Where: $f$ represents the frequency of the value; $n$ signifies the number of
population.

\textbf{Likert Scale.} The resulting weighted mean was interpreted in the range from
numbers 1 to 5, the lowest signifying that the response strongly disagreed with the
statement while the highest strongly agreed.

