\chapter{Results and Discussions}

The following pages present the study’s results alongside their interpretation and subsequent discussion. Each finding is examined in relation to the theoretical frameworks established in Chapter 1 — specifically Heritage Values Theory (Andrade et al., 2025), Gamification Theory (Oliveira \& Hamari, 2025), and the Technology Acceptance Model (Rahmi et al., 2026) — and is compared against relevant findings in the literature

\section{Results}

\subsection{Tinambac Landmarks Incorporated in the Gamified Application}

While considering the scope and delimitations stated within this study, the landmarks
chosen to be incorporated into the game are as follows: (1) Municipal Hall of Tinambac,
(2) St.\ Paschal Baylon Parish Church, (3) Caloco Beach, and (4) Cagliliog Beach
Resort. These landmarks were specifically chosen out of the 44 barangays in the
municipality of Tinambac, each landmark from a different barangay for both diversity and
relevance to the digital tour-themed game. The Municipal Hall of Tinambac is found in
barangay Binalay; St.\ Paschal Baylon Parish Church is in barangay San Pascual; Coloco
Beach is in barangay Caloco, a barangay along the road to the next municipality; and
Cagliliog Beach Resort is located in barangay Cagliliog.

These results align with the research of Sobarna et al.\ (2024), which stated that the
authenticity of digital objects, such as real-life counterparts of landmarks, directly
impacts user satisfaction and perceived authenticity. Furthermore, the success in
fostering appreciation for local beauty through gamification supports the strategy
outlined by Wu et al.\ (2023) \citep{wu2022}, who argued that gamifying culture is an
effective tool for maintaining cultural integrity and stimulating local development.

\subsection{Employed Approach Used to Provide Information About Tinambac}

During the development of the game, the project provides a gamified approach to tackle
the lack of alternative means by which the go-to places in the Municipality of Tinambac
are introduced to interested individuals. The employed approach uses combinations of:
(1) a quest system that pushes the player to explore the chosen landmarks sequentially;
(2) minigames within the game landmarks that provide further subtle information about
that landmark; and (3) real-life photos of the corresponding landmark and supporting
information presented after completing the minigame. The reward-based information model
creates a psychological ``information gap'' that motivates learning.

This approach reflects the ``serious game'' framework described by Dankov and Dankova
(2023) \citep{dankov2023}, who argue that educational video games are superior tools for
promoting cultural heritage because they foster active awareness through participation.
Furthermore, the success of the quest-based delivery supports the findings of Schultz
(2023) \citep{schultz2023} regarding the use of interactive narratives to engage players
with nostalgia and cultural reminiscing. By using NPCs as ``virtual guides,'' Project
Salubako effectively bridges the gap between digital storytelling and real-world
geographical education.

\subsection{Employed Design to Provide Entertainment on Top of Essential Information}

Project Salubako employed a linear, lighthearted story design that incorporates specific
landmarks, using the gamification theory as a driving force to provide the entertainment
a user or player needs on top of essential information relevant to its real-life
counterparts. This design comes in different instances within the gamified application;
jigsaw puzzles that use real-life pictures of a landmark are one such example. This
demonstrates that embedding cultural heritage content within a narrative-driven RPG
framework is a highly effective strategy for regional tourism promotion and pedagogical
efficacy.

However, the evaluation identified a ``mechanical discrepancy'' between informational
clarity and gameplay engagement. While players generally agreed the application provided
necessary entertainment, the core mechanics of puzzles and exploration received a lower
rating, suggesting that the ``serious'' component of the design outperformed its
intended depth. This engagement gap highlights a need for mechanical refinement, such
as implementing adaptive difficulty or more complex, context-linked puzzles, to better
satisfy the expectations of a target demographic already accustomed to high-engagement
RPG and MOBA gaming structures.

These findings resonate with the literature's consistent observation that effective
gamified heritage applications must integrate entertainment depth alongside informational
clarity \citep{ting2025} \citep{jo2025} \citep{fan2022}. The lower mechanics score also aligns with the
literature's caution that gamification functions as a double-edged mechanism
\citep{flavian2024} \citep{zhang2025} \citep{malik2024}.


\subsection{Level of Acceptability of the Gamified Application}

The foundational data of the study was collected from a survey with a total of 17
respondents, whose feedback was organized into four categories which are the results for
the 4 criteria in the level of acceptability of the gamified application, Salubako.
First is the player experience of the respondents; this category assessed the player's
overall experience in using the gamified application, which greatly provided insights
into the level of acceptability of the theme implementation that the study had. The
second category is about the knowledge and awareness of Tinambac of the respondents,
which serves as the crucial diagnostic tool, measuring the current understanding of the
subject matter; if the study provides information through gaming experience, it falls
under the level of acceptability of tourism information dissemination. And lastly, the
Perceived Impact and Recommendation of the Respondents contains the captured
forward-looking suggestions and participants' anticipated value of the project, guiding
the possible refinements and future implementation of Project Salubako to ensure its
relevance and effectiveness, which helped to determine the level of acceptability for
both the game mechanics and game element functionalities.


