\section{Summary of Findings}

The research focused on the issue regarding the lack of alternative options to showcase
landmarks from the Municipality of Tinambac in a more entertaining manner. The
researchers identified and sought to address the following problems: (1) which landmarks
to incorporate in the gamified application, (2) how it will provide information about
the landmarks, (3) what design it will employ to provide entertainment on top of the
information, and (4) the level of acceptability of the gamified application.

The research used a quantitative approach to gain concrete feedback from user testing.
The gathered data was divided into 4 categories: Demographic data, Player Experience,
Knowledge and Awareness of Tinambac, and Perceived Impact and Recommendation. All
categories contributed to gaining a better understanding of the effectiveness of the
gamified approach for promoting the local tourism of the Municipality of Tinambac.

\section{Conclusions}

The findings of the study showed the effectiveness of a gamified approach to tackling the lack of an alternative means for cultural preservation and promoting local tourism, which was made possible through using a gamified application.

The first problem was addressed though the process in which researchers chose 4 specific landmarks from the 44 barangays of the
Municipality of Tinambac: the Municipal Hall of Tinambac (barangay Binalay), St.\
Paschal Baylon Parish Church (barangay San Pascual), Caloco beach, and Cagliliog beach.
The game incorporated each landmark in a respective manner.

The gamified application employed real-world
assets, landmark names, and cultural nuances, as well as mini-game or quest completion
prompts, to provide information about each landmark. The overall map within the gamified
application also served as a medium to disseminate information by providing a layout of
the Municipality of Tinambac with pinned locations for the incorporated landmarks.

The gamified application
employed combinations of a quest system for the sequential exploration of the landmarks,
interactive mini-games within each landmark, and real-life photos with corresponding
information made possible by game interactions and the completion of mini-games.

The game was successful in its informational role---participants strongly agreed that
it provided clear and useful information (mean 4.3). It sparked curiosity about the
locality (mean 3.5) and increased appreciation through real-life settings (mean 3.9).
Players found the game engaging and fun (mean 3.1) and felt it effectively provided
entertainment (mean 3.3). The game's atmosphere, including sound and music (mean 3.6),
contributed positively to the player experience. These results suggest that the strongest
aspect of the application was not only the presence of information itself, but the way
that information was delivered through gameplay. The dialog system appears to have made
the content easier to understand, while the quest flow and progression mechanics helped
players connect each task with a specific landmark and its cultural context. This likely
explains why the information-related item received the highest mean compared with the
more moderate scores for entertainment and curiosity. 

These findings are consistent with
the Technology Acceptance Model because they show that clear, useful, and accessible
content supports user acceptance of the application. They also reinforce Heritage Values
Theory by showing that players did not merely encounter digital scenery; instead, they
engaged with landmark representations that conveyed cultural meaning and encouraged
greater appreciation of Tinambac's heritage. They also support the reviewed literature
on Laro ng Lahi-inspired and other localized heritage games, which argues that the use
of culturally specific content can successfully build appreciation and awareness.
Nevertheless, Salubako partially contrasts with some gamified tourism studies because
its highest performance was in informational clarity rather than in entertainment depth
or recommendation behavior, indicating that its present strength is as a heritage
education and information tool first, and as a tourism engagement platform second.

\section{Recommendations}

Based on the findings of this study, the following recommendations are proposed for further improvement on the delivery of the concept of using a gamified approach in cultural preservation and local tourism which was the foundation of "Salubako" as a gamified application.

First, using virtual reality (VR) for further enhancement of both
entertainment and immersion to the gamified approach. As well as choosing more landmarks
to provide diversity for the player and adding a layer to tour length and
interactiveness in consideration of each added landmark. Future versions may also assign
distinct chapter goals per landmark, such as a civic-history task in the Municipio, a
heritage trivia sequence in the church, and exploration-based collection tasks in the
beach areas, so that each location offers a more memorable identity.

Second, provide other means to disseminate
information, such as using interactable signs, NPC interactions, and better exploration
opportunities for the user or player. More specifically, the game may include optional
NPC dialogue trees, collectible journal pages, landmark stamp cards, and short audio or
text lore pop-ups that are unlocked after a player completes an objective in a location.

Third, add side activities or characters that provide
information on top of the main progression of the game. Place an option in the main
menu for manual viewing of available relevant information about the landmarks
incorporated in the game. For the 13+ age demographic, more suitable side activities may
include clue-hunt quests, photo-matching challenges using real landmark images,
dialog-based decision tasks, simple pattern or symbol puzzles tied to local culture, and
timed but low-frustration exploration goals. Reward structures may also be improved by
adding collectible badges, chapter completion stamps, unlockable character dialogue,
cosmetic items, or an in-game heritage album that expands after each accomplished task.

Lastly, the primary constraint on the
entertainment factor was the player's enjoyment of the core game mechanics, such as
puzzles and exploration, which received the weakest rating (mean 3.2). The mechanics
themselves require refinement to maximize player satisfaction. Concretely, this may
include replacing overly simple tasks with multi-step environmental puzzles, adding hint
systems so younger players are not discouraged, introducing tiered rewards for full
chapter completion, and designing short optional challenges that reward exploration
without forcing excessive repetition.

